<h1>Molecular Genetics</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Wed Mar 7, 2007; substantive revision Thu Mar 26, 2026</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
The term <em>molecular genetics</em> sometimes refers to (1) a
fundamental theory alleging that genes direct all life processes
through the production of proteins and RNAs (ribonucleic acids),
sometimes to (2) a more modest, basic theory about the replication and
expression of DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid), and sometimes to (3) an
investigative approach applied throughout biomedical science that is
based on investigative strategies grounded in the basic theory about
genes. This entry briefly summarizes the basic knowledge of molecular
genetics and surveys philosophical research on the subject,
considering all three senses of the term. The focus is on the
traditional issue of theoretical reduction as an account of the
molecularization of genetics as well as on more recent work that
attends to investigative rather than theoretical and explanatory
reasoning.</p>
</div> 

